pr_review_comment_body:
What I'm suggesting makes no copies. Something like

```C++
class Alphabet {
public:
  Alphabet(const char *config_file) {
  ...
  const std::string& StringFromLabel(const int& label) const {
    assert(label < size_);
    return label_to_str_[label];
  }
  ...
};
```

Along with
```C++
...
const std::string& str = mPriv->alphabet->StringFromLabel(character);
...
```

I'd like to request that we take the same approach as we did with chunk here. Import the method at toplevel, then use it directly inside the code without the lodash prefix. The `for (const x in foo)` approach is IMO less clear.

So change this to:

```js
import chunk from 'lodash/chunk';
import forIn from 'lodash/forIn';
```

The other option would be to split the funciton in two (since there are two purposes):

```python
def _get_pb_property_value(message_pb, property_name)
    """Return a message field value."""
    all_fields = set([field.name for field in message_pb._fields])
    if property_name not in all_fields:
        raise ValueError('Message does not contain %s.' % (property_name,))
    return getattr(message_pb, property_name)

def _assert_pb_property_value(message_pb, property_name, expected_value):
    """Raise if pb field does not exist, or does not match `expected_value`."""
    if _get_pb_property_value(message_pb, property_name) != expected_value:
        raise ValueError('Message returned %s value disagreeing '
                         'with value passed in.' % (property_name,))
```

Do you mean something like 
"""
    if (alpha != 0) {
      gradParameter.map(parameter, (g, p) => {
        ev.plus(g, if (ev.isGreater(p, ev.zero)) ev.one else ev.negative(ev.one))
      })
    }
"""
that will a bit slower but without additional buffer, which leads less memory. 
which one do you think better?

Are you proposing we do something like the following?
```
#define TEST_TABLE(FIXTURE, TEST) \
  TEST_F(FIXTURE, TEST) {         \
    test = this;                  \
    TEST(job_id_, client_);       \
  }

TEST_MACRO(TestGcsWithAe, TestTableLookupFailure);
TEST_MACRO(TestGcsWithAsio, TestTableLookupFailure);
#if RAY_USE_NEW_GCS
TEST_MACRO(TestGcsWithChainAe, TestTableLookupFailure);
TEST_MACRO(TestGcsWithChainAsio, TestTableLookupFailure);
#endif
<and other tests>
```

If so, should I refactor the existing TEST_F in this file that is not affected by this PR?  For example, the current state of the PR left 
```
TEST_F(TestGcsWithAe, TestLogLookup) {
  test = this;
  TestLogLookup(job_id_, client_);
}

TEST_F(TestGcsWithAsio, TestLogLookup) {
  test = this;
  TestLogLookup(job_id_, client_);
}
```
untouched.
